<br>
Having said that, everytime I come to the raid discussion forum one of the top 10 threads here is related to this issue.  As everyone knows by now, higher level resources are thin and the demand for them nearing a peak.  Most raids are planned to occur based around PST time (where I would venture to guess most of the player base on the server is located) and I'm sure little thought is given to the next day's raid start time.  The result is guilds like E.T. show up for their raid (which they probably schedule around GMT time), but parts (or even) all the zone mobs may not be spawned.  Thus, their reservation is wasted and they wonder why they bother to comply only to be stepped on by the rest of us.<br>
<br>
Many of the posts I read are sympathetic to the plight of Lanos and the rest of E.T., but noone has stepped up to propose a solution.<br>
<br>
Would E.T. and everyone else support changing the raid system so that non-U.S. guilds (how many are there?), if they &quot;win&quot; a reservation slot, are autmatically given the next spot as well to assure that they can enjoy the same priviledge of a fully spawned plane that we do?  <br>
<br>
A couple concerns:<br>
<br>
Is squeezing out that extra mob in a 48-hour period of time so important that we alienate our non-US friends who are not able to play on our U.S. schedule?<br>
<br>
How many guilds would this affect?  E.T. for sure.  Soul of Samurai?  How many others?<br>
<br>
How could this proposed change to the system be abused?<br>
<br>
<br>
Avoreen Azurelight<br>
Realm of Brell Serilis<br>
 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#313532><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title><A HREF="http://www.ezboard.com/promotions/csc.html" TARGET="_blank" ><IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/image/cscicon2.gif" WIDTH="20" HEIGHT="20" BORDER="0" align="absmiddle"></A> <A HREF=http://pub13.ezboard.com/udelsonorablackthorne.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Delsonora Blackthorne</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle><font color=#FFFF66>Brell Board Administrator <img src=http://www.brellserilis.net/images/goldstartr.gif align=middle><br>NWN Board Administrator</font></span><br>  Posts: 2236<br> <font color=#CC9900>(5/25/01 11:23:44 am)</font><br>     <br>Community Supporter<br> <BR><img src=http://www.brellserilis.net/images/gabby.gif width=101 height=80></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Accomodating Non-US Players</span><hr size=1> Thanks for posting this. Yeah, i think Europeans get the shaft in general, not just because of our scheduling system.<br>
<br>
One thing to keep in mind is that, we have been actively trying to improve the calendar over the past 6 months. We see that there are major problems. Well, all we get is a bunch of complaints for it. If we make a decision to fix something which is horribly broken, we get flamed because we didn't let everyone vote first. If we put something up to vote, we get flamed because we did that.<br>
<br>
This is a tough situation with the timezones and such. On the surface i don't see a way to accomodate our Euro neighbors without putting out players here in the states. Setting a time limit on a raid is something we can't enforce. A raid takes as long as a raid has the people to continue fighting, basically.<br>
<br>
Fair or not, the european player base is really small compared to the US playerbase, which unfortunately puts them in the minority. I have complete and utter sympathy for Lanos who is an old friend, and his guild. I just don't know a fair way to handle that, and we are almost to the point where no matter what we do, someone is gonna hate us for it. Kinda leaves us with not too many options.<br>
<br>
So, whether or not you came up with a proposal, you could count out half of the server supporting it. Someone is always going to feel that others are digging in their candy dish.. <p><b>The Many Faces of Blackthorne</b><br>
Kess 51 Rogue (retired)<br>
Delsonora 52 Mage (retired)<br>
Proud Alumnus of Warriors of Wrath<br></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#414141><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub13.ezboard.com/uthoricthemad.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Thoric the Mad</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Brell's man of Nomex</span><br>  Posts: 316<br> <font color=#CC9900>(5/25/01 11:48:13 am)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Accomodating Non-US Players</span><hr size=1> What Dels said. I sympathize with them but they are a tiny minority of the raiding populace. I don't feel the need to change anything as a result. They kinda knew what they were in for when they decided to play a game that was based in San Diego with a 70%+ US playerbase, ya? <p>ICQ#-105127301<BR>
<A HREF="http://sr.amiga.tm/" TARGET="_new"><IMG ALT="Silent Redemption Member" BORDER=0 SRC="http://home1.gte.net/res007bh/Thoricwarlordsig_copy.gif"></A> </p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#313532><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub13.ezboard.com/unicophorus.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Nicophorus</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC=http://homepages.go.com/~aela_eq/Shield.gif BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Less Talk, More Fight</span><br>  Posts: 825<br> <font color=#CC9900>(5/25/01 12:17:32 pm)</font><br>    <BR><img src=http://homepages.go.com/~aela_eq/Shield.gif border=0></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Accomodating Non-US Players</span><hr size=1> Do remember though that there is a tradeoff.<br>
<br>
While it's true that certain resources (the reserved ones is what we're talking about) work maybe 60/40 in favor of the US playerbase, the Europeans aren't exactly getting ONLY the shaft.<br>
<br>
You've been able to level up with about 1/3 the serverpopulation that the average US player faces.  What you define as a 'crowded' dungeon we find comepletly empty as we're used to seeing 3x that.  This has provided access to experience, entertainment, and (lets be honest it always involves) loot that the US player has to play 'harder' for.<br>
<br>
Also, the reservation 'timer' is based on midnight PST (which is early AM hours for most of the US), however the European player has the advantage of being able to reserve their spot from work... or at least during wakened hours, so the system gives you a slight advantage there (personally I'd much rather try hitting a reservation at 9AM ish my time rather than staying awake till 2AM to do it).<br>
<br>
So, it ain't all bad...<br>
<br>
BTW, most raids on BSNet schedule using PST since this board uses PST.  This board uses PST since that's where Verant is located and they schedul patches on PST.  The US playerbase is pretty evenly spread over four timezones (discounting Alaska and Hawaii) and we have a hard time keeping that straight... GMT just boggles many of us (I work more globally but still have to look at office timepieces for London, Tokyo, etc. time).<br>
<br>
That's all filler material though.  The real issue here is raids... specifically planar raids and yes that IS a problem.  I honestly don't see a SOLUTION to that problem.  I do think there is one workaround... communication.  Adun could (sorry to volunteer a mod) post a reminder to the prior days raid (during his 'posted' post) reminding them that a European raid is scheduled in advance.  <br>
<br>
Another thought (someone grab a clock and see if this is feasible) is to treat a European reservation as a reservation for the day BEFORE it really is and still allow a US reservation on the same calendar day as the European actual raid (for instance, it might have been possible for a late US raid to have happened on 24-May in Hate following the European raid, while disallowing a 23-May raid for US... basically treating the 24-May European raid as a 23-May raid and letting a late starting 24-May raid go up... this would work out (I'm thinking) fairly well on weekday raids since they tend to run fewer hours.  Weekend raids are all day affairs anyhow so they're beside the point I guess.<br>
<br>
Those are just thunks though, I've not actually added the hours and compared spawntimes so I could be a bit off or completely wrong.<br>
